Default keyword allows us to define methods with implementation inside an interface.
It was introduced in Java 8 to provide backward compatibility and avoid breaking existing implementations

Java does NOT support multiple inheritance with classes:
--------------------------------------------------------

    class A {}
    class B {}
    class C extends A, B {} // ❌ Not allowed

But Java does allow multiple interface implementation:
--------------------------------------------------------

    interface A {}
    interface B {}
    class C implements A, B {} // ✅ Allowed

Why Was default Introduced?
---------------------------
    Before Java 8:

    - Interfaces could only have abstract methods

    If you added a new method to an interface,
    👉 all implementing classes would break ❌

    To solve this problem, Java 8 introduced:
    ✅ default methods
        - A default method is a method inside an interface that has a body. It provides a default implementation.
        - Default methods are not mandatory to override
        - Child class can override if needed
        - They help maintain backward compatibility

    What If Two Interfaces Have Same Default Method?

        If two interfaces have the same default method, the implementing class must override it to resolve the conflict.

        Example:
            class Test implements A, B {

                public void show() {
                    A.super.show();   // choose explicitly
                }
            }
            
